limiting\",\n        \"gap\": \"test_quota_admin_routes_rate_limited_per_principal proves the per-principal-not-per-IP dimension well (the discriminating shape), but only exercises GET's throttle exhaustion directly (principal A's second GET 429s); DELETE is only proven to NOT be throttled for principal B (which still has capacity), never driven to its own 429. A route-specific throttle-key bug on DELETE alone (e.g. a copy-paste that hard-codes a different bucket name) would not be caught.\",\n        \"severity\": \"low\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"area\": \"AC9 / DELETE validation - query-param type coercion\",\n        \"gap\": \"The 422 tests cover missing field, invalid customer_id shape, injection payload, and an unknown extra param, but never a wrong-TYPE value for a query param that pydantic could silently coerce (e.g. metric as a list via repeated ?metric=a&metric=b, or a customer_id supplied as an array-like bracket syntax). FastAPI's Query() binding for a str field on repeated params is worth a boundary test given DELETE takes only query params (no body) and typed coercion mistakes are exactly the class of bug allowlist-based schemas are meant to catch.\",\n        \"severity\": \"low\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"area\": \"quotas_repo.list_quotas / delete_quota - ordering under NULL or duplicate collisions\",\n        \"gap\": \"AC1's ordering test seeds three distinct (customer_id, metric) pairs; it never seeds two rows differing only by metric under case-insensitive-adjacent values (e.g. 'API' vs 'api') to prove the RDS default collation genuinely produces a stable order across runs (plan's own open question 2 flags this as an accepted risk, not resolved) -- current tests can't distinguish 'stable because ORDER BY is present' from 'stable because the specific seeded values happen to sort unambiguously under any collation'.\",\n        \"severity\": \"low\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"area\": \"AC19 / GET safe-error path\",\n        \"gap\": \"The GET forced-error test monkeypatches quota_service.list_quotas at the service layer, which is one level above the actual DB I/O (quotas_repo.list_quotas). It proves the route -> error-handler wiring, but doesn't force a failure inside the repository's own text()-execute call (e.g. a real asyncpg DBAPIError) to prove the repository layer itself doesn't leak a raw SQLSTATE/DSN fragment before the service-level catch. The DELETE variant has the same shape but is partially compensated by its own fail-closed row-survival assertion, which does exercise real DB state.\",\n        \"severity\": \"low\"\n      },\n      {\n        \"area\": \"Mutation coverage\",\n        \"gap\": \"No mutation run has ever executed against quotas_repo.py/quota_service.py/routes/quotas.py/schemas/quotas.py (see mutation.note) -- so 100%-branch-covered lines in these modules are unverified against e.g. an off-by-one in the ORDER BY clause, a flipped 404-vs-204 boundary condition, or a swapped AND/OR in delete_quota's WHERE clause. Line/branch coverage alone cannot catch a mutant that changes behavior without changing which lines execute (e.g. AND -> OR in the WHERE clause would still hit the same lines).\",\n        \"severity\": \"medium\"\n      }\n    ]\n  }\n}\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":364,"cache_read_input_tokens":106503,"output_tokens":1894,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":364},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":1894,"cache_read_input_tokens":106503,"cache_creation_input_tokens":364,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":364,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":null},"requestId":"req_011CcshBfEE6pKb5f4LgFikg","attributionAgent":